SIG Sauer P6.  West German (no Exeter crap here) SIG in 9x19 with a single-stack 8-round mag.  Very heavy DA trigger (not going off unless you want it to, so if you're worried about an AD then this is the style of gun for you), nice crisp SA trigger.  I've discovered I shoot Glocks better though (even with their notoriously bad grip angle), so I'm going to switch to that.  

The SIG has been my carry gun and has never had any sort of issue beyond the fact that the slide has failed to lock back on the last round a couple times (I think 3 times in about 400 rounds).

Gun is clean and in working order.  Shows external holster wear from being carried by the police, but internals are great.

postcontent:
Very nice Spanish Mauser FR-8 in .308 caliber! These guns were reworked from M.1943 Mauser rifles, and this one is accordingly stamped on the receiver, "Fabrica De Armas La Coruna 1955". The receiver displays a slightly fading Spanish crest. FR-8 was used for practice by Spanish soldiers before they were issued CETME assault rifles. The rifle has a fake gas tube installed under the barrel, to make it look like the CETME rifle. This fake gas tube is actually a cleaning kit container (the cleaning kit is not included). This gun has stronger, 1898-type action than FR-7, which was build on 1893-type action. Straight bolt handle. Stock with pistol grip. The stock does not display any markings. All matching serial numbers (the matching serial numbers are stamped on the receiver, barrel and on the bolt only; all the remaining parts do not display any numbers, which is correct for this model). No provision for the cleaning rod. CONDITION: Excellent, as rebuilt by Spanish arsenal. Most of phosphate finish is still on metal. Very nice stock has been filled in two places. Excellent bore with strong and shiny rifling. Strong action. All the internal parts of the rifle are in excellent condition, with little visible wear. Mechanically, the rifle is in great condition.

title: For Sale:  British Army Baker Musket (Blackpowder Flintlock) New and Unfired
postcontent:
Selling a great reproduction of the famous Baker Rifle (1806 model) with rounded patch box, rounded lock with goose-necked cock. This rifle was made by the same manufacturers who made for the Rifles for the Television Series Sharpe's Rifles. This Rifle is unfired and in new condition.

This is a beautiful replica of this famous rifle.  The rifle corps of the British Army, along with a number of other foreign armies financed by Great Britain, used the Baker Rifle throughout the Napoleonic Wars. In North America, the rifle companies of the 60th Regiment used the Baker Rifle during the invasion of Maine in 1814.  The famous 95th Rifles used them at New Orleans in 1815.   

The vent is not drilled from the pan into the barrel yet, but any gunsmith can do this. The frizzen is case hardened to produce good sparks. The seamless tempered barrel is made of high-carbon steel (type:BS970 no.080M40) and the breech is threaded. The barrel is not rifled (.62 Cal). 

Originally bought from MilitaryHeritage.com in Canada.
